  <static seed="74" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions50.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{1}{7} + \frac{23}{35}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{18}{35}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator. In this case, the least common multiple of <m>7</m> and <m>35</m> is <m>35</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{1}{7}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>35</m>, we multiply <m>5</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}-\frac{1}{7} \amp = -\frac{1 \cdot 5}{7 \cdot 5}\\ \amp = -\frac{5}{35} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the addition. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   -\frac{1}{7} + \frac{23}{35}
        \amp = -\frac{5}{35} + \frac{23}{35} \\
        \amp = \frac{-5 + 23}{35} \\
        
        \amp = \frac{18}{35}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
